Not to mention the off putting signs everywhere. "Bathrooms for customers only". Seriously? You're located in a tiny shopping center with a bank and a dance studio, how much foot traffic could you possibly be getting that is going to use your toilet and not buy something?? Just seems tacky and cheap.

My biggest stink is their 40 Cent transaction fee for purchases under 5 dollars. I am familiar with merchant fees charged my Visa, MC, Amex & Discover. Even on a 5 dollar purchase at a merchant charge of 5% of the purchase only comes out to .25 cents (15 Cent surplus). So they are blindly charging a random number and profiting on the rest.(Fees are much closer to 2% and 3%). 3% on 5 dollars is 15 cents. That is a 25 cent profit on every transaction under 5 dollars. A purchase under $5 is pretty easy to do if you just want a coffee or a muffin. Now am I really bothered by a 40 cent charge added to my 5 dollar coffee? No, not really. But the principle of this is wrong. Charging your customers an additional fee for trying to pay? That screams "struggling business". It's the 21st century, Many people don't pay with cash, as paying with a bank card is far more convenient. If you want the business, bite the bullet and pay the transaction fee.

My advice? If a business is in the red over a matter of 40 cents and having people use their water by flushing their toilets, they probably shouldn't be in business.

My biggest stink is their 40 Cent transaction fee for purchases under 5 dollars. I am familiar with merchant fees charged my Visa, MC, Amex & Discover. Even on a 5 dollar purchase at a merchant charge of 5% of the purchase only comes out to .25 cents (15 Cent surplus). So they are blindly charging a random number and profiting on the rest.(Fees are much closer to 2% and 3%). 3% on 5 dollars is 15 cents. That is a 25 cent profit on every transaction under 5 dollars. A purchase under $5 is pretty easy to do if you just want a coffee or a muffin. Now am I really bothered by a 40 cent charge added to my 5 dollar coffee? No, not really. But the principle of this is wrong. Charging your customers an additional fee for trying to pay? That screams "struggling business". It's the 21st century, Many people don't pay with cash, as paying with a bank card is far more convenient. If you want the business, bite the bullet and pay the transaction fee.

My advice? If a business is in the red over a matter of 40 cents and having people use their water by flushing their toilets, they probably shouldn't be in business.
